<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>217</anchor>  <taxon>Theorem</taxon> <addr>axt-000X</addr>  <route>axt-000X.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>9</month> <day>15</day></date>  <title>Hausdorff property and filter bases</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  A space <tex>X</tex> is <link href="axt-000Q.xml" type="local" title="Hausdorff">Hausdorff</link> iff every <link href="axt-000Y.xml" type="local" title="Filter base">filter base</link> has at
  most one limit.
</p><p>TODO: write the proof.</p></mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>218</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>axt-000Y</addr>  <route>axt-000Y.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>9</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author>Ayberk Tosun</author> </authors> <title>Filter base</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  A <em>filter base</em> on a nonempty set <tex>X</tex> is a family <tex>\{  B_i  \} _{i  \in  I}</tex>  of subsets of <tex>\mathcal{P} (X)</tex> satisfying the following properties:
  <ol>    <li><tex>I  \neq   \emptyset</tex> and <tex>B_i  \neq   \emptyset</tex> for each <tex>i  \in  I</tex></li>    <li>      For any two <tex>i, j  \in  I</tex>, there exists some <tex>k  \in  I</tex> such that
      <tex>B_k  \subseteq  B_i  \cap  B_j</tex>.
    </li>  </ol></p><p>  Adapted from the definition in page 21 of
  <link href="bridges-topological-and-uniform-2022.xml" type="local" title="Bridges' lecture notes">Bridges' lecture notes</link>.
</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>219</anchor>  <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>axt-000Q</addr>  <route>axt-000Q.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>9</month> <day>15</day></date> <authors><author>James R. Munkres</author> </authors> <title>Hausdorff space (point-set)</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>  A space <tex>X</tex> is called <em>Hausdorff</em> if for any two distinct points <tex>x_1,
  x_2  \in  X</tex>, there exist a <em>disjoint</em> pair of open neighbourhoods <tex>U_1, U_2
   \in   \mathcal{O} ( X )</tex>, of <tex>x_1</tex> and <tex>x_2</tex>.
</p><p>  Adapted from <link href="munkres-topology-2000.xml" type="local" title="Topology by Munkres">Topology by Munkres</link>.
</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks/> <references/></backmatter></tree>